-- S.Korea stocks finish flat, won up on foreign net buying
-- By Jungmin Jang
-- Thu May 15, 2014 02:10AM EDT
-- None



SEOUL, May 15 (Reuters) - South Korean shares closed flat after briefly hitting a more than five-month high on Thursday, as investors took profits from a five-day winning streak, while robust capital inflows into the stock market supported the won <KRW=>.

The Korea Composite Stock Price Index (KOSPI) <.KS11> closed down 0.03 percent at 2,010.20 points after rising to an intraday high of 2,015.37, the strongest level since Dec. 3, 2013. Foreign investors purchased a net 332.4 billion Korean won ($323.42 million), picking up a net 891.7 billion won worth of KOSPI shares in last three sessions.